y fails to solve the crime, but also confronts insoluble mysteries of interpretation and identity. As the contributors to Detecting Texts contend, such stories belong to a distinct genre, the "metaphysical detective story," in which the detective hero's inability to interpret the mystery inevitably casts doubt on the reader's similar attempt to make sense of the text and the world.Detecting Texts includes an introduction by the editors that defines the metaphysical detective story and traces its history from Poe's classic tales to today's postmodernist experiments. In addition to the editors, contributors include Stephen Bernstein, Joel Black, John T. Irwin, Jeffrey T. Nealon, and others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aDetective and mystery storiesxHistory and criticism. 0aExperimental fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aFictionx20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFictionxTechnique. 0aFictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMetaphysics in literature. 0aRoman expérimentalxHistoire et critique. 0aRoman policierxHistoire et critique. 0aRomanx20e sièclexHistoire et critique. 0aRomanxTechnique. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Mystery & Detective.2bisacsh1 aMerivale, Patricia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSweeney, Susan Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220545940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812205459423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.c